[1] Take-all - wheat
[2] Phoma, light leaf spot, sclerotinia - oilseed rape

******
[1] Take-all - wheat
Date: Wed 24 Sep 2008
Source: Farmers Guardian [edited]
<http://www.farmersguardian.com/story.asp?sectioncode=19&storycode=21500>


High take-all infections found in cereal trials
-----------------------------------------------
Root evaluations at HGCA [Home Grown Cereals Association] Recommended
List second cereal trial sites across the country have highlighted a
major build-up of take-all infections for the 2nd year in a row.

Averaging 61 on a 1-100 scale, the take-all index this summer [2008]
was the highest since routine assessments began in 2005. Severe
infections (indexing more than 60) were recorded on 63 percent of the
sites compared to 40 percent in last year's [2007] high take-all
season. "These results confirm that take-all has built up
substantially over the past season from the high levels of infection
recorded in our 2007 monitoring," said Monsanto agronomist, Rob
Plaice who co-coordinated the monitoring.

"While the wet summer once again enabled many crops with quite badly
compromised root systems to survive without excessive yield loss, it
also allowed the fungus to continue proliferating widely. What's
more, soils damaged by one of the most difficult harvests on record
and very wet seedbeds provide the ideal conditions for early take-all
development this autumn [2008]. So 2009 looks set to present a
particular disease challenge for second cereal growers."

Mr Plaice advises growers drilling wheat or barley as a second cereal
this autumn [2008] to use a seed treatment effective against take-all
as a matter of course unless the risk from the disease has
historically been very low -- regardless of variety or drilling date.
Delayed drilling alone is most unlikely to prevent serious damage
this season, he said.

--
